{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YLoZaGmud8VaE5nhRuvumW","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Prometheus has a ClusterRoleBinding which means it has cluster-wide permissions to discover endpoints. Good. I can now create a `ServiceMonitor` in the `cockroachdb` namespace.\n\nLet me create a `ServiceMonitor` that:\n1. Lives in the `cockroachdb` namespace (matching the Prometheus `serviceMonitorNamespaceSelector`)\n2. Selects the CockroachDB services by label `app.kubernetes.io/name: cockroachdb`\n3. Scrapes the `http` port (8080) at path `/_status/vars`\nI'm deciding whether to target the headless `crdb-cluster` service for per-pod scraping, since it creates individual endpoints for each pod in the StatefulSet, giving me properly labeled per-pod metrics. I could also use label selectors to target multiple services with a single ServiceMonitor. I'm realizing the key distinction: a ClusterIP service endpoint in Prometheus resolves to the actual pod IPs, not the virtual IP. So selecting by the shared labels would still result in scraping all three pods through the headless service plus the same three pods again through the ClusterIP service's resolved endpoints. The cleanest solution is to add a specific label to just the headless service to differentiate it, or rely on the fact that I only need to configure the ServiceMonitor to target the headless service by name. Both services would scrape the same three pods, creating duplicates, so I need to be selective. The cleanest approach is to add a label to the headless service and have the ServiceMonitor select only services with that label, ensuring I'm monitoring from just one service.\n\nActually, I could just use the public service directly since Prometheus will discover all three pod endpoints through it anyway. Let me check the endpoints to confirm this works.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usag